Problem:
-------
You are given the root of a binary tree, and your task is to return its top view. The top view of a binary tree is the set of nodes visible
when the tree is viewed from the top.

Note:
Return the nodes from the leftmost node to the rightmost node.
If multiple nodes overlap at the same horizontal position, only the topmost (closest to the root) node is included in the view. 

Example:
Input:Binary Tree: 1 2 3 4 10 9 11 -1 5 -1 -1 -1 -1 -1 -1 -1 6
Output: Top View: [4, 2, 1, 3, 11]

Solution:
--------
class Solution {
    class Pair {
        Node node;
        int hd;
    
        Pair(Node node, int hd) {
            this.node = node;
            this.hd = hd;
        }
     }
    public ArrayList<Integer> topView(Node root) {
        // code here
         ArrayList<Integer> ans = new ArrayList<>();
         if(root==null){
             return ans;
         }
         TreeMap<Integer,Integer> map = new TreeMap<>();
         Queue<Pair> queue = new LinkedList<>();
         queue.add(new Pair(root,0));
         while(!queue.isEmpty()){
             int size=queue.size();
             for(int i=0;i<size;i++){
                 Pair p = queue.remove();
                 Node curr = p.node;
                 int hd = p.hd;
                 if(!map.containsKey(hd))
                    map.put(hd,curr.data);
                 if(curr.left!=null){
                     queue.add(new Pair(curr.left,hd-1));
                 }
                 if(curr.right!=null){
                     queue.add(new Pair(curr.right,hd+1));
                 }
             }
         }
         for(int h:map.keySet()){
             ans.add(map.get(h));
         }
         return ans;
    }
}

Time Complexity: O(N logN)
Space Complexity: O(N)
